-- Crude Options Volatility Falls to One-Week Low as Futures Slip
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-05-07T20:39:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-07/crude-options-volatility-falls-to-one-week-low-as-futures-slip.html
Crude options volatility fell to a
one-week low as the underlying futures slipped for the first
time in four days.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 21.66 percent at 4:05 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , down from 22.98 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery declined 54
cents to settle at $95.62 a barrel on the Nymex.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
September $85 puts, which rose 10 cents to $1.33 a barrel on
volume of 5,021 contracts at 3:48 p.m. June $110 calls were the
second-most active, unchanged at 2 cents a barrel on volume of
2,583 lots.  Puts accounted for 55 percent of electronic trading volume
today. Bearish bets made up 51 percent of yesterdayâ€™s volume of
161,805 contracts.  July $90 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 12,590 contracts changing hands. They
fell 9 cents to 99 cents a barrel. June $100 calls increased 2
cents to 29 cents a barrel on 9,020 lots.  Open interest was highest for June $80 puts with 39,543
contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 38,008 and
December $110 calls with 34,112.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-
outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
